Hypothesis 1

friends_vs_happiness <- responses %>% select( Number.of.friends, Happiness.in.life) %>% arrange(desc(Number.of.friends))
plot(jitter(Number.of.friends)~jitter(Happiness.in.life), data=friends_vs_happiness)

Hypothesis 2

gender_vs_happiness <- dplyr::select(responses, Gender, Happiness.in.life)%>% filter(!is.na(Gender)) %>% filter(!is.na(Happiness.in.life))
boxplot(Happiness.in.life~Gender, data=gender_vs_happiness)

Hypothesis 3

happiness_vs_age <- responses %>%
na.omit() %>%
group_by(Age) %>%
summarise(avg_happiness = mean(Happiness.in.life))
plot(avg_happiness~Age,data= happiness_vs_age)

Hypothesis 4

God_vs_Loneliness <- responses %>%
na.omit() %>%
group_by(God) %>%
summarise(avg_Loneliness = mean(Loneliness))
plot(avg_Loneliness~God,data= God_vs_Loneliness)

Here we found that people who believe in God considered themselves much less lonely than those who did not. This observation is interesting because it shows the role of religion in their emotions.

Hypothesis 5

finance_vs_clothes <- responses %>% select( Finances, Branded.clothing) %>% arrange(desc(Finances))
plot(jitter(Finances)~jitter(Branded.clothing), data=finance_vs_clothes)

Here we found that most people consider themselves in the middle of the road for both the amount of money they save and their preference for branded over non-branded clothing. This relationship is interesting because we can also see that more people save no money and strongly prefer branded clothing than save all their money and do not prefer branded clothing, which is unexpected.

Hypothesis 6

truth_vs_lie <- dplyr::select(responses, Only.child,Number.of.siblings )%>% filter(!is.na(Only.child)) %>% filter(!is.na(Number.of.siblings))
boxplot(Number.of.siblings~Only.child, data=truth_vs_lie)

Here we found that some people who said they are an only child also said that they have siblings. This is interesting because it shows what potential errors there could be in the data, or perhaps the incidence of people lying on their survey.
